The worldwide distribution of various symbionts isolated from invasive 
 Mimosa species may be the result of selection by soil characteristics and other ecological factors (
 Elliott et al., 2009; 
 Melkonian et al., 2014; 
 de Castro Pires et al., 2018). In the present study, the community composition in the five provinces were unbalanced: 
 P. mimosarum was more abundant in Yunnan; 
 P. phymatum was more in Guangdong and Guangxi; 
 Rhizobium stains were mostly from Hainan; and the minor group 
 P. caribensis was only isolated from 
 M. pudica plants grown in Guangdong and Guangxi. These geographic distributions implied an interaction among the plants, the rhizobial species, and the environment factors, as described for rhizobia associated with soybean (
 Zhang et al., 2011).
